ugh, we check the residual.\n    \n    # Wait, the task says "consistently runs faster".\n    # If I use power iteration and it fails, I\'ll have to use eig, \n    # which might make it slower on average.\n    \n    # Let\'s try to use power iteration for a fixed number of steps \n    # and then check the residual.\n    \n    # Actually, for 10x10, let\'s just use np.linalg.eig but try to \n    # see if we can optimize the call.\n    \n    # Let\'s try power iteration with a fixed number of iterations \n    # and then check the residual.\n    \n    # If the residual is small, we return. Otherwise, we use eig.\n    \n    # Let\'s try this:\n    n = A.shape[0]\n    x = np.random.randn(n)\n    for _ in range(20):\n        x_new = A @ x\n        norm = np.linalg.norm(x_new)\n        if norm < 1e-15:\n            x = x_new\n            break\n        x = x_new / norm\n    \n    # Estimate eigenvalue\n    # lambda = (x.T @ A @ x) / (x.T @ x)\n    # Since x is normalized, lambda = x.T @ A @ x\n    lam = x.T @ (A @ x)\n    \n    # Check residual\n    res = np.linalg.norm(A @ x - lam * x)\n    if res < 1e-6:\n        return lam, x\n    else:\n        # Fallback to eig\n        eigenvalues, eigenvectors = np.linalg.eig(A)\n        idx = np.argmax(np.abs(eigenvalues))\n        return eigenvalues[idx], eigenvectors[:, idx]\nEOF\n'})
